 American society as postracial, in which race seldom affects outcomes. Conversely, in discussing their experiences within predominantly black spaces, they rejected the idea of white privilege, often angrily, and instead focused on what they saw as the racial privilege of blackness. Throughout, Bell underscores the significance of white victimization narratives in black spaces and their repercussions as the United States becomes a majority-minority society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxCrimes againstxPublic opinion. 0aEducation, UrbanzUnited States. 0aRacism in educationzUnited States. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 0aTeachers, WhitezUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aTeachingxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aWhitesxRace identityzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSL40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478021933?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478021933423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478021933/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075418-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  